03927nam a22006255i 9780271022710DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710227107 a10.1515/97802710227102doi  a(DE-B1597)583712  a(OCoLC)1253313051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a1842221 aCorrigan, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlato's Dialectic at Play :bArgument, Structure, and Myth in the Symposium /cElena Glazov-Corrigan, Kevin Corrigan. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Symposium is one of Plato's most accessible dialogues, an engrossing historical document as well as an entertaining literary masterpiece. By uncovering the structural design of the dialogue, Plato's Dialectic at Play aims at revealing a Plato for whom the dialogical form was not merely ornamentation or philosophical methodology but the essence of philosophical exploration. His dialectic is not only argument; it is also play. Careful analysis of each layer of the text leads cumulatively to a picture of the dialogue's underlying structure, related to both argument and myth, and shows that a dynamic link exists between Diotima's higher mysteries and the organization of the dialogue as a whole. On this basis the authors argue that the Symposium, with its positive theory of art contained in the ascent to the Beautiful, may be viewed as a companion piece to the Republic, with its negative critique of the role of art in the context of the Good. Following Nietzsche's suggestion and applying criteria developed by Mikhail Bakhtin, they further argue for seeing the Symposium as the first novel. The book concludes with a comprehensive reevaluation of the significance of the Symposium and its place in Plato's thought generally, touching on major issues in Platonic scholarship: the nature of art, the body-soul connection, the problem of identity, the relationship between mythos and logos, Platonic love, and the question of authorial writing and the vanishing signature of the absent Plato himself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aGlazov-Corrigan, Elena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271022710?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271022710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271022710/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK